  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks against money laundering. Key examples include:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- An international organization setting global standards\n- Recommends policies to combat money laundering and terrorist financing\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides recommendations for preventing money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Sets international banking standards to prevent financial crimes\n\n5. Individual Country Laws\n- Most nations have specific anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Often require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate customer identification and record-keeping\n\nThese frameworks typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Monitor and report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n- Conduct risk assessments\n\nPenalties for non-compliance can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.\n\nWhile international frameworks exist, enforcement and implementation vary by country.",
